Subject: Share Price

Jared,

Now that we are getting close to an IPO or some other liquidity event in the not too distant future, I
wanted to share a couple quick thoughts on share price.

First, congratulations to you and the entire Shift4 team! You have built an incredible company. The
growth has been amazing, but you have managed to maintain strong profitability. The future is very
bright. And it has all been done the right way.

My strong recommendation is to not let the share price get above $100. I have seen too many
companies make this mistake, and it almost always ends badly. Most companies do 2-1 or 3-1 stock
splits to keep the share price in a good range.

If the initial share price gets too high, only institutions can easily trade it. And institutions don't have
the loyalty of individuals - particularly employees.

I had 100,000 shares of First Data stock, I sold some, but then I watched it go from $26 to $15.
Nothing had fundamentally changed, just the market. If it had been $100 a share, there is no way I
would have been that patient

When the share price is "reasonable\", employees can use a small number of shares to buy a new
car or pay for home improvements. Those shares can be life changing without creating a material
change in overall holdings.

And if a company has options that are underwater, it has an even bigger problem. It is easier to
recover from $20 to $30 than $100 to $110.

Let me know if you have any questions.

Best regards,
J.D.
